{
  "_provenance": {
    "source": "Calibrated to the AHRQ Medical Expenditure Panel Survey (MEPS), Household Component.",
    "method": "Service-line frequencies and lognormal severities are set so that simulated mean annual spend by age and the well-documented concentration of spending (top 5% of people account for ~50% of expenditures) reproduce published MEPS aggregates. Allowed amounts reflect typical U.S. commercial negotiated prices.",
    "note": "These are population calibration constants, not individual records. Each patient's profile is their own data; the Monte-Carlo samples from these real-data-calibrated distributions."
  },
  "concentration": {
    "meanAnnual": 6700,
    "medianAnnual": 1300,
    "top1pct": 0.22,
    "top5pct": 0.5,
    "top10pct": 0.66,
    "bottom50pct": 0.03
  },
  "frailty": {
    "sigma": 1.5,
    "note": "Person-year latent multiplier, mean 1 (lognormal). Drawn once per simulated year and applied to the Poisson rate of every acute service line, so a person's risk is correlated across services instead of independent. With mean fixed at 1 it preserves age-band mean spend, while sigma controls how skewed the population is: this is what reproduces the MEPS concentration (top 5% ~ 50% of spend) and the catastrophic-year tail that independent per-service draws cannot. Chronic meds and guaranteed planned events are exempt (they are known, not stochastic)."
  },
  "ageBands": [
    { "key": "0-17", "min": 0, "max": 17, "meanAnnualSpend": 2300 },
